	<div class="columnGroup first">				
		
<h1 itemprop="headline"  class="articleHeadline">Other Voices: Conflicts, Opinions and More Disclosure; What Reporters Think</h1>



	<h6 class="dateline">Published: February 4, 2007</h6>
<div class="shareTools shareToolsThemeClassic articleShareToolsTop"
	data-shares="facebook,twitter,google,email,showall|Share,print,singlepage,reprints,ad" 
	data-title="Other Voices: Conflicts, Opinions and More Disclosure; What Reporters Think" 
	data-url="http://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9802E2D7123FF937A35751C0A9619C8B63" 
	data-description="<br>Re ''Drawing a Line'' (Jan. 28):
<p>
  I commend you for your work to tighten the ethical standards of The Times's outsider contributors. In the past, I would have concluded that the paper was aware of these questionable ties but didn't see them as unethical. Seems many of the ''problems'' at The Times can be dealt with by tightening up procedures and some good old-fashioned fact-checking.
<p>"></div>
<meta name="emailThisHash" content="EzmAAotroqy6OpkH/kP3CA">
<div class="articleBody">

        
    
                                            <p itemprop="articleBody">
                    <br>Re ''Drawing a Line'' (Jan. 28):        </p>
                        <p itemprop="articleBody">
                    I commend you for your work to tighten the ethical standards of The Times's outsider contributors. In the past, I would have concluded that the paper was aware of these questionable ties but didn't see them as unethical. Seems many of the ''problems'' at The Times can be dealt with by tightening up procedures and some good old-fashioned fact-checking.        </p>
                        <p itemprop="articleBody">
                    Then I got to the section about Michael Gordon, The Times's chief military correspondent, and what he said on the ''Charlie Rose'' show. Mr. Gordon's personal opinion would have seemed natural for an American at one time. Now, it's ''over the line.''        </p>
                        <p itemprop="articleBody">
                    What line would that be? I hope this line is between public reporting and private sentiments. I shudder to think about what is on the other side of this line if this is not the case. Could it have been a claim of defeat?
<br>
<br>ANDREA ECONOMOS
<br>Scarsdale, N.Y., Jan. 28, 2007
<br>
<br>I sense an inconsistency in your column. Two freelancers are chastised for concealing economic ties that might influence their judgment, and Michael Gordon, The Times's chief military correspondent, is berated for revealing a policy opinion that may influence his.        </p>
                        <p itemprop="articleBody">
                    I would prefer more disclosure of the policy views of reporters. Unless The Times deliberately hires imbeciles, reporters will have opinions about the issues they cover. They can try to minimize the effect of those opinions on the facts they choose and the words they use. But partial success is the best they can hope for.        </p>
                        <p itemprop="articleBody">
                    Here's an alternative approach. Require all reporters with bylines to post the following on The Times's Web site: who got their vote in the major contests in the last election and a brief summary of their views on several topics of current importance, for example, the Iraq war, the administration's fiscal policy and the candidates now seeking the presidential nomination.        </p>
                        <p itemprop="articleBody">
                    This strikes me as being no more than the disclosure The Times requires of financial interests.
<br>
<br>HARRY ALLAN
<br>Hackensack, N.J., Jan. 28, 2007
<br>
<br>I agree that The Times should report the news impartially, and I can understand a policy that frowns on a reporter expressing a personal opinion in public on a national program. I suppose that is to be contrasted with the leeway allowed reporters in ''news analysis'' columns.        </p>
                        <p itemprop="articleBody">
                    But the issue is a lot less clear than one might infer from your treatment of it. News reporting usually involves judgment, and while many reporters might try to avoid forming opinions on controversial issues on their beat, I am sure that at least some of them have opinions on these issues. If reporters do have opinions on such issues, I would prefer to know them so that I can better evaluate the information in their news reports.        </p>
                        <p itemprop="articleBody">
                    Assuming a well-disciplined newsroom with good editors, I do not see the harm in Michael Gordon's having expressed his opinion -- labeled clearly as his personal opinion -- outside of the newspaper.
<br>
<br>JONATHAN MALLAMUD
<br>Jenkintown, Pa., Jan. 28, 2007
<br>
<br>You and Philip Taubman, The Times's Washington bureau chief, can only wish to be transmogrified through time into the old Soviet ''minder'' system. Anyone who steps out of line is watched and reported, then you apparatchiks gleefully slug back a vodka.        </p>
                        <p itemprop="articleBody">
                    The screed against Michael Gordon was disgusting. We live in America. You have no right to chill him with your reproaches. If you don't want him to appear with Charlie Rose, then put it in his contract.
<br>
<br>ROD GOODWIN
<br>Philadelphia, Jan. 29, 2007
<br>
<br>I'm not sure why you and Philip Taubman saw or heard anything inappropriate in Michael Gordon's statement that he thought the latest temporary escalation, or whatever we're calling it, was worth trying.        </p>
                        <p itemprop="articleBody">
                    Mr. Gordon's opinion might well be wrong, but he is the co-author of two books that analyze and criticize American military strategy in Iraq -- not just ''Cobra II,'' but also ''The Generals' War'' -- and his opinion is quite consistent with the views he expressed, and The Times presumably encouraged him to express, in those two books. Shouldn't his status as an author and analyst qualify him as an honorary opinion columnist for purposes of stating opinions during television appearances?
<br>
<br>MARK REGAN
<br>Bethel, Alaska, Jan. 28, 2007
<br>
<br>May I suggest that you've got the Michael Gordon issue backward? If Mr. Gordon has personal views about the war, of course they are going to influence his reporting. So it is better if he and The Times tell us what his personal biases are.        </p>
                        <p itemprop="articleBody">
                    Your suggestion -- that Times reporters conceal their personal views, or pretend they don't have any -- hides from the reader a basic element necessary to judge the reporter's credibility. You seem to think that if Mr. Gordon doesn't express his opinion on TV, then he doesn't have an opinion on the war. But he does have an opinion. Why would you want to hide it from readers?        </p>
                        <p itemprop="articleBody">
                    The best approach would be for The Times to continue publishing Mr. Gordon's articles, but to append an italic note each time saying, ''Michael Gordon believes the United States can achieve victory in Iraq and that a troop escalation will help do that.''
<br>
<br>T. R. REID
<br>Princeton, N.J., Jan. 28, 2007
<br>
<br>The writer, a reporter, is a visiting professor of humanities at Princeton University.        </p>
                    </div>
	</div>
